pull_request.title: Bump mini_magick from 4.13.2 to 5.3.0
pull_request.body:
Bumps [mini_magick](https://github.com/minimagick/minimagick) from 4.13.2 to 5.3.0.
Release notes

Sourced from mini_magick's releases.

v5.3.0

  • Actually require Ruby 2.5+ in the gemspec.
  • Fix Ruby 2.5 compatibility when using MiniMagick.restricted_env configuration.
  • Drop benchmark dependency.
  • Fix keyword argument forwarding when trying to call MiniMagick.compare(errors: false)

v5.2.0

  • Added MiniMagick.restricted_env configuration for stopping IM command from inheriting environment variables from the parent process.
  • Fixed "ambiguous * has been interpreted as an argument prefix" warning

v5.1.2

  • Add benchmark gem to runtime dependencies

v5.1.1

  • Add logger gem to dependencies for Ruby 3.4+.

v5.1.0

  • New cli_env configuration was added for setting extra environment variables for every CLI command:

    MiniMagick.configure do |config|
  config.cli_env = { "MAGICK_MEMORY_LIMIT" => "128MiB" }
end

  • New graphicsmagick configuration was added for telling MiniMagick to use GraphicsMagick instead of MiniMagick:

    MiniMagick.configure do |config|
  config.graphicsmagick = true # prepend all commands with "gm"
end

    Previously, the recommended approach was setting MiniMagick.cli_prefix = "gm", but that doesn't work when ImageMagick 7 is installed, as in that case MiniMagick will try to prepend magick on top of gm.

v5.0.1

  • MiniMagick::Image#write doesn't delete the internal tempfile anymore, which restores use cases like:

    image = MiniMagick::Image.open("...")
image.resize("500x500")
image.write("foo.jpg")
image.blur
image.write("bar.png")

  • Prevented MiniMagick::Image#to_ary being called by ruby in certain cases, such as [image].flatten(1).

v5.0.0

Improvements

... (truncated)

Commits
  • c53b8bb Bump to 5.3.0
  • eda3dde Bump ruby 2.5+ requirement in the gemspec
  • ed928b1 Add spec for the keyword arguments
  • 6de850a Try using ENV.to_h for compatibility with Ruby 2.5 (#593)
  • c1b2e2c Fix option forwarding in MiniMagick::Tool.new (#596)
  • dfd3de0 Fix typo in README: change tmdir to tmpdir in configuration example (#595)
  • 23239db Drop benchmark dependency (#592)
  • 7f25f72 Fix testing with current versions of ImageMagick (#591)
  • 34433dc Bump to 5.2.0
  • bbcb06f Use Hash#slice
  • Additional commits viewable in compare view

release.name: 0.2.0 - 2025 Update compatiblilty, haptics, articulated hands and more
release.body:
## Version 0.2.0 - 2025-08-17

Hello, this is a small update in response to the [Subnautica 2025 Patch](https://unknownworlds.com/en/news/subnautica-2025-patch).
The mod is compatible and should work fine with the new update from my limited testing, but I still found some minor quirks I want to fix and polish in the coming weeks.

Additionally, some of the improvements from the BZ Mod by @jbusfield made it into this patch!
You can now enable articulated/tracked hands and game and UI haptics. I still want to improve the haptics though, since I found it vibrating in an alert pattern sometimes without a reason.
Unfortunately, the physical driving system from the BZ Mod was not compatible with the input changes in the original game, but I will try to get it working in a future update again.
Also thanks to @LeeTwentyThree for starting off this update with a pull request and updates for BepInEx.

### Features

- Contributions from the BZ Mod (from @jbusfield)
- Optional WIP Haptics
- New Ambient Occlusion
- Articulated / SteamVR Tracked Hands

### Bug Fixes

- Sprinting respects the input switch setting now
    - Add default bindings for sprinting on Oculus and Holographic (Windows MR)
        - You hold one or both grip buttons to sprint
    - **NOTE:** Sprinting is still too slow though, I am working on it
- Remove the early VR-Check which could improve starting issues for some people

### Documentation

- Update README with more help and better structure
- Mention Below Zero port in the FAQ

## Contributions/Pull Requests

* Added Haptics, Articulated Hands options by @jbusfield in https://github.com/Okabintaro/SubmersedVR/pull/80
* Update csproj and dependencies for 2025 patch + minor code fixes that shouldn't affect logic by @LeeTwentyThree in https://github.com/Okabintaro/SubmersedVR/pull/185

## New Contributors
* @LeeTwentyThree made their first contribution in https://github.com/Okabintaro/SubmersedVR/pull/185

**Full Changelog**: https://github.com/Okabintaro/SubmersedVR/compare/0.1.6...0.2.0

pull_request.title: Create .NET 8 Fluent Garmin Library with FIT SDK Integration, Enhanced Repeat Structure Support, and Dependency Injection Interface
pull_request.body:
This PR implements a complete .NET 8 library that provides a fluent wrapper around Garmin's FIT SDK for creating workout files with proper repeat structure support and dependency injection capabilities. The library enables developers to easily generate Garmin-compatible workout files using an intuitive, builder-pattern API that follows Garmin's recommended patterns for intervals.

## Key Features

**Fluent API Design with Dependency Injection**: The library provides an easy-to-use builder pattern with full DI support:

```csharp
// Register for dependency injection
services.AddTransient<IWorkoutBuilder, WorkoutBuilder>();

// Use in controllers/services
public class WorkoutService
{
    private readonly IWorkoutBuilder _builder;
    
    public WorkoutService(IWorkoutBuilder builder)
    {
        _builder = builder;
    }
    
    public WorkoutModel CreateWorkout()
    {
        return _builder
            .Name("Morning Run")
            .Sport(Sport.Running)
            .WarmUp(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
            .AddTimeStep("Main Set", 20, 4, TargetType.HeartRate)
            .CoolDown(5, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
            .Build();
    }
}
```

**Interval Workouts with Explicit Option Objects**: Structured interval training with clear parameter configuration:

```csharp
var intervalOptions = new IntervalOptions 
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Distance,
    Value = 400,
    Zone = 4,
    TargetType = TargetType.Speed
};

var recoveryOptions = new RecoveryOptions
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Time,
    Value = 120,
    TargetType = TargetType.Open
};

var intervals = new WorkoutBuilder()
    .Name("Track Intervals")
    .Sport(Sport.Running)
    .WarmUp(10, 1)
    .AddIntervals("5x400m", 5, intervalOptions, recoveryOptions)
    .CoolDown(10, 1)
    .Build();
```

**Enhanced Method Naming**: Clear distinction between different types of workout steps:
- `AddTimeStep()` and `AddDistanceStep()` for individual workout segments (easy runs, tempo efforts, etc.)
- `AddIntervals()` for structured interval training with repeat patterns
- `AddRepeat()` for custom repeat structures with child steps

**Explicit Parameter Structure**: The `AddIntervals()` method requires explicit option objects for improved code clarity:
- Uses `IntervalOptions` and `RecoveryOptions` parameter objects that must be created and passed in
- Removes convenience overloads that built options internally for better API explicitness

**Proper Repeat Structure Support**: Uses Garmin's FIT SDK repeat patterns instead of manually creating individual steps:
- `AddIntervals()` method for easy interval creation with automatic repeat structure
- `AddRepeat()` method for custom repeat patterns with child steps
- Proper FIT file generation with parent repeat steps, child steps, and completion steps

**Comprehensive Target Support**: Full support for all Garmin target types including zones and custom ranges:
- Heart Rate zones (1-5) and custom BPM ranges (150-170)
- Speed zones (1-5) and custom speed ranges  
- Power zones (1-5) and custom wattage ranges
- Cadence custom ranges

**Enhanced Builder Methods**: Flexible warm-up and cool-down methods that accept target types:

```csharp
.WarmUp(15, 1, TargetType.Power)   // Power-based warm-up for cycling
.CoolDown(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)  // HR-based cool-down
```

## Implementation Details

The library uses proper Garmin FIT SDK repeat patterns and dependency injection best practices:
- **IWorkoutBuilder Interface**: Enables clean dependency injection patterns for testability and flexibility
- **Repeat Steps**: Parent steps with `RepeatUntilStepsCmplt` duration type
- **Child Steps**: Interval and recovery steps contained within repeat structure  
- **Completion Steps**: Define how many times to repeat the pattern

This approach is more efficient and follows Garmin's recommended practices compared to manually creating individual interval steps.

## Project Structure

The solution file has been moved to the `src/` folder for better organization, with all projects properly referenced.

## Documentation

The README includes comprehensive examples covering:
- Basic workout patterns (warm up, main set, cool down) using `AddTimeStep`
- Interval workouts using repeat structures with explicit option objects
- Fartlek workouts with mixed interval patterns
- Custom repeat patterns and advanced usage
- Dependency injection setup and usage patterns
- Complete API documentation with real-world examples

## Testing

The library includes comprehensive test coverage with 24 unit tests covering:
- Model functionality and validation
- Fluent builder pattern behavior including new repeat methods
- File generation capabilities with repeat structure support
- All example workout scenarios using repeat patterns
- Custom target range functionality
- Dependency injection interface support
- Edge cases and error handling

All tests pass and the library builds without warnings on .NET 8.

Fixes #1.

pull_request.title: Fix: Convert linked image URLs to relative paths
pull_request.body:
Fixes #2

Adds support for converting linked image URLs to relative paths. Previously, only simple image references were converted, but linked images (`[![alt](url)](link_url)`) kept their external URLs.

**Changes:**
- Added regex pattern to handle `[![alt](url)](link_url)` format
- Convert external link URLs to relative paths when they match downloaded images
- Maintains existing functionality for simple image references
